ce:section.ce:para:
The sensitivity performance of BN-CDs towards various ISO concentrations was exhaustively discussed. It could be plainly suggested from Fig. 4
                        A, the emission intensity of the sensing system visibly decreased in the presence of IOS, indicating that the ISO could quench the fluorescence of BN-CDs. The ln(F0/F) value increased with ISO amount varying from 0 to 50 μM and displayed a remarkable linear relationship with ISO amount in the range of 0–50 μM (F0 and F refer to the emission intensity of sensing system in the absence and presence of ISO). The corresponding linear equation was fitted as ln(F0/F) = 0.054[ISO] + 0.0085 (R2 = 0.9978) (Fig. 4B). The LOD value was 0.056 μM in the light of the expression 3b/k (b refers to the standard deviation of the emission intensity of sensing system without addition of ISO (15 times), k represents the slope of fitting curve). Meanwhile, the blue fluorescence decreased gradually with ISO concentration increasing from 0 to 50 μ M. From Fig. S4, the sensing process of BN-CDs for ISO was carried out swiftly in just 30 s, suggesting the immense potential of BN-CDs as sensitive fluorescence sensors for the determination of ISO. Compared with other methods, our developed sensor displayed simple, sensitive, and rapid detection of ISO, and had wider linear range and lower LOD value (Table 1
                        ).
